she were to have both. So basically the vaginal canal is just shorter or 
what is called a pouch. (Meaning no opening toward the inside of the body). 
I am the same way. But I'm a lesbian so it really doesn't matter in my case 
about carrying children and how "normal" my vagina is. It's all good with 
my girlfriend and I. If you want to truly educate yourself on it, just 
Google MRKH Syndrome. Instead of passing judgement and spreading hate. Also 
if you have daughters who aren't developing at a "normal" rate, please get 
them to the doctor to get tested.MRKH Syndrome does not ONLY affect the

to ensure that your daughter will start leading a healthier life sooner.﻿

Mayer-Rokitansky-Küster-Hauser syndrome -
Mayer-Rokitansky-Küster-Hauser (MRKH) syndrome is a disorder that occurs in 
females and mainly affects the reproductive system. This condition causes 
the vagina and uterus to be underdeveloped or absent. Affected women 
usually do not have menstrual periods due to the absent uterus. Often, the 
first noticeable sign of MRKH syndrome is that menstruation does not begin 
by age 16 (primary amenorrhea). Women with MRKH syndrome have a female 
chromosome pattern (46,XX) and normally functioning ovaries. They also have 
normal female external genitalia and normal breast and pubic hair 
development. Although women with this condition are usually unable to carry 
a pregnancy, they may be able to have children through assisted 
reproduction.
Women with MRKH syndrome may also have abnormalities in other parts of the 
body. The kidneys may be abnormally formed or positioned, or one kidney may 
fail to develop (unilateral renal agenesis). Affected individuals commonly 
develop skeletal abnormalities, particularly of the spinal bones 
(vertebrae). Females with MRKH syndrome may also have hearing loss or heart 
defects.MRKH syndrome affects approximately 1 in 4,500 newborn girls.This 
syndrome is quite rare.﻿

Less often, MRKH syndrome is passed through generations in families. Its 
inheritance pattern is usually unclear because the signs and symptoms of 
the condition frequently vary among affected individuals in the same 
family. However, in some families, the condition appears to have an 
autosomal dominant pattern of inheritance. Autosomal dominant inheritance 
means that one copy of the altered gene in each cell is typically 
sufficient to cause the disorder, although no genes have been associated 
with MRKH syndrome.

The story about the guy who lost a shit load of water weight is feasible. 
I'm not sure about 24 pounds in 24 hours, but almost half of that is most 
definitely possible. Old school wrestlers would do it all the time, in 
order to cut weight and wrestle in lower weight classes, myself included. 


At 7 years old, I was prepping for Jr. Olympic wrestling qualification 
tournament, and chewed on ice cubes & ate grapes the last day before 
weigh-ins. When I wrestled in high school, along with starvation during the 
week, I'd wear a plastic bag underneath a Sauna Suit, underneath several 
layers of sweatshirts & pants at practice as well as overnight when 
sleeping. Hell yeah, we now know that was dangerous as fuck, but back then 
it was part of a wrestler's training. 


At the end of my Junior year wrestling season, I was listed as having 04% 
body fat and yeah, that was almost unheard of even back then. It was 3/4 of 
the way through my Senior year wrestling season, when I learned a huge 
lesson. I didn't make weight for my 140 pound weight-class. Was only over a 
pound, but that didn't matter. I could not wrestle. Until my coach told me 
that if I want to, I could wrestle in place of our 160 pound guy who 
suffered a broken ankle the week before. I jumped at that offer. But one 
thing to understand, is that most every weight-class was made up by 
wrestlers who dropped about two classes. Basically, the guys I wrestled 
that day, were the 185+ pound football players. 


Well after pinning my first 3 opponents, all combined in less than 2 
minutes, I earned a spot for the Championship Match at 160 weight-class 
which floored everyone. I wish that I could end with me saying I won the 
championship, but I didn't. I was wrestling a guy who placed 3rd at States 
the year before and was undefeated going into the match with me. Ok, my 
record had suffered on 2 losses that year but that was at 140lbs. Well to 
wrap this up, the score was 5-2 with one minute remaining in the last 
period. With about 20 seconds left, I attempted a hip toss, but my grip 
slipped and he flattened me. Yeah, with 10 seconds left he pinned me. 


The next day, while talking with my mom about my 2nd place finish, it hit 
me! Why the hell did I lose so much weight every year, starving & little to 
drink, in order to cut down a few weight classes? The answer was never 
clear up to that point, because everyone did it. The realization that if I 
had to do it all over again, I would have NEVER cut weight beyond a few 
pounds, and wrestled that weight-class. Oh, to have back all of the dessert 
at Thanksgiving & Christmas, that I had to pass up during wrestling 
season... peace﻿
